
Templates are frontend-owned until AST finishes preparing them.

AST owns composition, slot routing, wrapper application, folding, runtime render-plan preparation, reactivity metadata and const page fragment output.
HIR only lowers final runtime templates.

## Main paths

- `src/compiler_frontend/ast/templates/`
- `src/compiler_frontend/ast/templates/tir/`
- `src/compiler_frontend/ast/module_ast/finalization/`
- `src/compiler_frontend/hir/`
- `src/backends/backend_feature_validation.rs`

## AST template ownership

AST owns:

- parsing template bodies after tokenization and emitting them into TIR
- composing slots, inserts, wrappers and child templates in TIR
- folding fully constant templates into string literals
- preserving structured template `if` and `loop` bodies for runtime lazy lowering
- preparing runtime slot source/site plans after schema extraction and contribution routing
- validating const-required template control flow before HIR
- rejecting escaped slot/insert helper artifacts that are invalid after composition/routing
- preserving runtime templates as runtime expressions
- replacing runtime templates with owned runtime handoff payloads before HIR
- removing helper-only template artifacts before HIR
- emitting builder-facing const top-level fragment metadata

This isn't backend work.
Backends should not parse directives or rebuild slot schemas.

## TIR

TIR is the AST-local Template IR.
It stores parsed and finalized template nodes, summaries, wrapper sets, slot plans and HIR handoff data.

TIR is internal and behaviour-preserving.
It doesn't change the template language.

TIR is the authoritative internal representation for templates during AST processing.
The parser emits templates directly into the module-scoped `TemplateIrStore`, and `Template` is a thin TIR handle while AST is active. The TIR registry and stores are dropped before the completed `Ast` is returned: HIR and backends never see TIR IDs, stores, views, overlays or registry values. HIR receives only folded string constants or neutral owned runtime handoff payloads.
The direction should stay clear: template semantics live in one AST-owned representation, not in scattered backend-specific plans.

## HIR handoff

HIR only lowers final runtime templates that remain after AST folding.

HIR doesn't:

- parse directives
- validate slot schemas
- rebuild missing render plans
- carry backend-specific template control-flow nodes
- carry compile-time page fragments

Runtime template control flow lowers inline as ordinary HIR branches, loops, accumulator appends and AST-prepared runtime slot source/site plans in the enclosing function.

Runtime slot applications are routed during AST preparation and lower through ordinary runtime string accumulators.

## Page fragments

Top-level runtime templates remain runtime code inside active-root `start()`.
Top-level const templates fold in AST into compile-time fragments with runtime insertion indexes.
Builders merge compile-time fragments into the runtime fragment list.

HIR doesn't need to know how an HTML page is assembled.
That belongs to builders.

## Reactivity V1

Reactivity V1 is frontend-owned source and template metadata that later stages preserve for backend feature validation and backend lowering.

It must not become:

- a second type system
- a general closure model
- a function-value surface
- a backend render-plan language

Stage ownership:

- declaration syntax parses `$Type`, `$=` and `$T` parameter access markers as syntax only
- AST resolves the underlying ordinary `TypeId`, assigns source identity, validates `$(source)` template subscriptions and preserves reactive template string metadata
- HIR carries backend-facing reactive source/template metadata and reachability facts
- borrow validation treats subscriptions as read-only source dependencies, not active borrow lifetimes
- backend feature validation applies the selected target contract before lowering
- runtime reactive behaviour remains backend-owned artifact policy

## Reactive subscriptions

A template subscription captures stable source identity and read-only subscription metadata.
It doesn't capture a mutable borrow, copied value or computed expression.

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    [source]     -- snapshot template read
    $(source)    -- reactive subscription
]

The first form is a snapshot read. The second captures stable reactive source
identity and subscription metadata.

Borrow validation records conservative invalidation facts for writes and mutations that may dirty reactive sources.
Ordinary alias and exclusivity rules still apply to the underlying values.

## Common mistakes

- Asking HIR to parse template directives.
- Letting a backend validate slot schemas.
- Carrying compile-time page fragments inside HIR.
- Treating TIR as a language feature instead of an AST representation.
- Treating reactive subscriptions as mutable borrows.
- Turning reactivity into closures or function values.
- Letting runtime template control flow become backend-specific nodes.

